# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algebraic-effects
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] In computer science, a **continuation** is an abstract representation of the control state of a computer program.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations are useful for encoding other control mechanisms in programming languages such as exceptions, generators, coroutines, and so on.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The "**current continuation**" or "continuation of the computation step" is the continuation that, from the perspective of running code, would be derived from the current point in a program's execution.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The term *continuations* can also be used to refer to **first-class continuations**, which are constructs that give a programming language the ability to save the execution state at any point and return to that point at a later point in the program, possibly multiple times.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The earliest description of continuations was made by Adriaan van Wijngaarden in September 1964.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Wijngaarden spoke at the IFIP Working Conference on Formal Language Description Languages held in Baden bei Wien, Austria.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] As part of a formulation for an Algol 60 preprocessor, he called for a transformation of proper procedures into continuation-passing style, though he did not use this name, and his intention was to simplify a program and thus make its result more clear.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Reynolds brought the term *continuation* into prominence in their work in the field of denotational semantics that makes extensive use of continuations to allow sequential programs to be analysed in terms of functional programming semantics.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Steve Russell invented the continuation in his second Lisp implementation for the IBM 704, though he did not name it.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Reynolds (1993) gives a complete history of the discovery of continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] First-class continuations are a language's ability to completely control the execution order of instructions.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] They can be used to jump to a function that produced the call to the current function, or to a function that has previously exited.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] One can think of a first-class continuation as saving the *execution* state of the program.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] True first-class continuations do not save program data – unlike a process image – only the execution context.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Scheme was the first full production system providing first "catch" and then call/cc.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations are also used in models of computation including denotational semantics, the actor model, process calculi, and lambda calculus.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] These models rely on programmers or semantics engineers to write mathematical functions in the so-called continuation-passing style.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] This means that each function consumes a function that represents the rest of the computation relative to this function call.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] To return a value, the function calls this "continuation function" with a return value; to abort the computation it returns a value.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Functional programmers who write their programs in continuation-passing style gain the expressive power to manipulate the flow of control in arbitrary ways.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The cost is that they must maintain the invariants of control and continuations by hand, which can be a highly complex undertaking (but see 'continuation-passing style' below).
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations simplify and clarify the implementation of several common design patterns, including coroutines/green threads and exception handling, by providing the basic, low-level primitive which unifies these seemingly unconnected patterns.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations can provide elegant solutions to some difficult high-level problems, like programming a web server that supports multiple pages, accessed by the use of the forward and back buttons and by following links.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The Smalltalk Seaside web framework uses continuations to great effect, allowing one to program the web server in procedural style, by switching continuations when switching pages.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] More complex constructs for which *"continuations provide an elegant description"* also exist.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] For example, in C, longjmp can be used to jump from the middle of one function to another, provided the second function lies deeper in the stack (if it is waiting for the first function to return, possibly among others).
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Other more complex examples include coroutines in Simula 67, Lua, and Perl; tasklets in Stackless Python; generators in Icon and Python; continuations in Scala (starting in 2.8); fibers in Ruby (starting in 1.9.1); the backtracking mechanism in Prolog; monads in functional programming; and threads.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] For a gentler introduction to this mechanism, see call-with-current-continuation.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] This example shows a possible usage of continuations to implement coroutines as separate threads.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] A program must allocate space in memory for the variables its functions use.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Most programming languages use a call stack for storing the variables needed because it allows for fast and simple allocating and automatic deallocation of memory.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Other programming languages use a heap for this, which allows for flexibility at a higher cost for allocating and deallocating memory.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Both of these implementations have benefits and drawbacks in the context of continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] In any language which supports closures and proper tail calls, it is possible to write programs in continuation-passing style and manually implement call/cc.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] (In continuation-passing style, call/cc becomes a simple function that can be written with lambda.) This is a particularly common strategy in Haskell, where it is easy to construct a "continuation-passing monad" (for example, the `Cont` monad and `ContT` monad transformer in the `mtl` library).
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The support for proper tail calls is needed because in continuation-passing style no function ever returns; *all* calls are tail calls.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] One area that has seen practical use of continuations is in Web programming.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The use of continuations shields the programmer from the stateless nature of the HTTP protocol.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] In the traditional model of web programming, the lack of state is reflected in the program's structure, leading to code constructed around a model that lends itself very poorly to expressing computational problems.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Thus continuations enable code that has the useful properties associated with inversion of control, while avoiding its problems.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] "Inverting back the inversion of control or, Continuations versus page-centric programming" is a paper that provides a good introduction to continuations applied to web programming.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Support for continuations varies widely.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] A programming language supports *re-invocable* continuations if a continuation may be invoked repeatedly (even after it has already returned).
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Re-invocable continuations were introduced by Peter J.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Landin using his **J** (for Jump) operator that could transfer the flow of control back into the middle of a procedure invocation.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Re-invocable continuations have also been called "re-entrant" in the Racket language.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] However this use of the term "re-entrant" can be easily confused with its use in discussions of multithreading.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] A more limited kind is the *escape continuation* that may be used to escape the current context to a surrounding one.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Many languages which do not explicitly support continuations support exception handling, which is equivalent to escape continuations and can be used for the same purposes.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] C's `setjmp/longjmp` are also equivalent: they can only be used to unwind the stack.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Escape continuations can also be used to implement tail call elimination.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] One generalization of continuations are delimited continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuation operators like `call/cc` capture the *entire* remaining computation at a given point in the program and provide no way of delimiting this capture.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Delimited continuation operators address this by providing two separate control mechanisms: a *prompt* that delimits a continuation operation and a *reification* operator such as `shift` or `control`.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations captured using delimited operators thus only represent a slice of the program context.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] Continuations are the functional expression of the GOTO statement, and the same caveats apply.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] While they are a sensible option in some special cases such as web programming, use of continuations can result in code that is difficult to follow.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] In fact, the esoteric programming language Unlambda includes call-with-current-continuation as one of its features solely because expressions involving it "tend to be hopelessly difficult to track down".
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The external links below illustrate the concept in more detail.
[src:algebraic-effects/continuation] The extent to which continuations can be used to explain other general phenomena in natural language is a topic of current research.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] They have been described as "functions whose execution you can pause".
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Melvin Conway coined the term *coroutine* in 1958 when he applied it to the construction of an assembly program.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The first published explanation of the coroutine appeared later, in 1963.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] There is no single precise definition of coroutine.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] 2. the execution of a coroutine is suspended as control leaves it, only to carry on where it left off when control re-enters the coroutine at some later stage.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] 3. whether a coroutine is able to suspend its execution from within nested function calls.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Such a coroutine is a *stackful coroutine*.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] One to the contrary is called *stackless coroutines*, where unless marked as coroutine, a regular function can't use the keyword `yield`.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The paper "Revisiting Coroutines" published in 2009 proposed the term *full coroutine* to denote one that supports first-class coroutine and is stackful.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Full Coroutines deserve their own name in that they have the same expressive power as one-shot continuations and delimited continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Full coroutines are either symmetric or asymmetric.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Importantly, whether a coroutine is symmetric or asymmetric has no bearing on how expressive it can be, though full coroutines are more expressive than non-full coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] While their expressive power is the same, asymmetrical coroutines more closely resemble routine based control structures in the sense that control is always passed back to the invoker, which programmers may find more familiar.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Subroutines are special cases of coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] When subroutines are invoked, execution begins at the start, and once a subroutine exits, it is finished; an instance of a subroutine only returns once, and does not hold state between invocations.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] By contrast, coroutines can exit by calling other coroutines, which may later return to the point where they were invoked in the original coroutine; from the coroutine's point of view, it is not exiting but calling another coroutine.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Thus, a coroutine instance holds state, and varies between invocations; there can be multiple instances of a given coroutine at once.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The difference between calling another coroutine by means of "yielding" to it and simply calling another routine (which then, also, would return to the original point), is that the relationship between two coroutines which yield to each other is not that of caller-callee, but instead symmetric.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Any subroutine can be translated to a coroutine which does not call *yield*.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Here is a simple example of how coroutines can be useful.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Suppose you have a consumer-producer relationship where one routine creates items and adds them to a queue and another removes items from the queue and uses them.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] For reasons of efficiency, you want to add and remove several items at once.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The queue is then completely filled or emptied before yielding control to the other coroutine using the *yield* command.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The further coroutines calls are starting right after the *yield*, in the outer coroutine loop.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Although this example is often used as an introduction to multithreading, two threads are not needed for this: the *yield* statement can be implemented by a jump directly from one routine into the other.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] However, coroutines are cooperatively multitasked, whereas threads are typically preemptively multitasked.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Coroutines provide concurrency, because they allow tasks to be performed out of order or in a changeable order, without changing the overall outcome, but they do not provide parallelism, because they do not execute multiple tasks simultaneously.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] It is possible to implement coroutines using preemptively-scheduled threads, in a way that will be transparent to the calling code, but some of the advantages (particularly the suitability for hard-realtime operation and relative cheapness of switching between them) will be lost.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a subset of coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] That is, since generators are primarily used to simplify the writing of iterators, the `yield` statement in a generator does not specify a coroutine to jump to, but rather passes a value back to a parent routine.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A number of implementations of coroutines for languages with generator support but no native coroutines (e.g.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Python before 2.5) use this or a similar model.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Using coroutines for state machines or concurrency is similar to using mutual recursion with tail calls, as in both cases the control changes to a different one of a set of routines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] However, coroutines are more flexible and generally more efficient.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Further, each mutually recursive call of a subroutine requires a new stack frame (unless tail call elimination is implemented), while passing control between coroutines uses the existing contexts and can be implemented simply by a jump.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Coroutines originated as an assembly language method, but are supported in some high-level programming languages.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Java does not have native or library support for coroutines, but it can call Kotlin coroutines `kotlinx.coroutines` (though this is not ideal and would require a Java wrapper over Kotlin).
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since continuations can be used to implement coroutines, programming languages that support them can also quite easily support coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] As of 2003, many of the most popular programming languages, including C and its derivatives, do not have built-in support for coroutines within the language or their standard libraries.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This is, in large part, due to the limitations of stack-based subroutine implementation.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] An exception is the C++ library Boost.Context, part of Boost, which supports context swapping on ARM, MIPS, PowerPC, SPARC and x86 on POSIX, Mac OS X and Windows.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Coroutines can be built upon Boost.Context.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Conditionals within the code result in the execution of different code paths on successive calls, based on the values of the state variables.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Another typical response is to implement an explicit state machine in the form of a large and complex switch statement or via a goto statement, particularly a computed goto.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Such implementations are considered difficult to understand and maintain, and a motivation for coroutine support.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Threads, and to a lesser extent fibers, are an alternative to coroutines in mainstream programming environments today.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Threads provide facilities for managing the real-time cooperative interaction of *simultaneously* executing pieces of code.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Threads are widely available in environments that support C (and are supported natively in many other modern languages), are familiar to many programmers, and are usually well-implemented, well-documented and well-supported.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] However, as they solve a large and difficult problem they include many powerful and complex facilities and have a correspondingly difficult learning curve.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] As such, when a coroutine is all that is needed, using a thread can be overkill.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] One important difference between threads and coroutines is that threads are typically preemptively scheduled while coroutines are not.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Because threads can be rescheduled at any instant and can execute concurrently, programs using threads must be careful about locking.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] In contrast, because coroutines can only be rescheduled at specific points in the program and do not execute concurrently, programs using coroutines can often avoid locking entirely.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This property is also cited as a benefit of event-driven or asynchronous programming.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since fibers are cooperatively scheduled, they provide an ideal base for implementing coroutines above.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] However, system support for fibers is often lacking compared to that for threads.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] In order to implement general-purpose coroutines, a second call stack must be obtained, which is a feature not directly supported by the C language.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A reliable (albeit platform-specific) way to achieve this is to use a small amount of inline assembly to explicitly manipulate the stack pointer during initial creation of the coroutine.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This is the approach recommended by Tom Duff in a discussion on its relative merits vs. the method used by Protothreads.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] On platforms which provide the POSIX sigaltstack system call, a second call stack can be obtained by calling a springboard function from within a signal handler to achieve the same goal in portable C, at the cost of some extra complexity.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] C libraries complying to POSIX or the Single Unix Specification (SUSv3) provided such routines as getcontext, setcontext, makecontext and swapcontext, but these functions were declared obsolete in POSIX 1.2008.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Once a second call stack has been obtained with one of the methods listed above, the setjmp and longjmp functions in the standard C library can then be used to implement the switches between coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] These functions save and restore, respectively, the stack pointer, program counter, callee-saved registers, and any other internal state as required by the ABI, such that returning to a coroutine after having yielded restores all the state that would be restored upon returning from a function call.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Minimalist implementations, which do not piggyback off the setjmp and longjmp functions, may achieve the same result via a small block of inline assembly which swaps merely the stack pointer and program counter, and clobbers all other registers.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This can be significantly faster, as setjmp and longjmp must conservatively store all registers which may be in use according to the ABI, whereas the clobber method allows the compiler to store (by spilling to the stack) only what it knows is actually in use.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Due to the lack of direct language support, many authors have written their own libraries for coroutines which hide the above details.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Russ Cox's libtask library is a good example of this genre.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] It uses the context functions if they are provided by the native C library; otherwise it provides its own implementations for ARM, PowerPC, Sparc, and x86.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Other notable implementations include libpcl, coro, lthread, libCoroutine, libconcurrency, libcoro, ribs2, libdill., libaco, and libco.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] In addition to the general approach above, several attempts have been made to approximate coroutines in C with combinations of subroutines and macros.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Simon Tatham's contribution, based on Duff's device, is a notable example of the genre, and is the basis for Protothreads and similar implementations.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] C++20 introduced standardized coroutines as stackless functions that can be suspended in the middle of execution and resumed at a later point.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The suspended state of a coroutine is stored on the heap.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Implementation of this standard is ongoing, with the G++ and MSVC compilers currently fully supporting standard coroutines in recent versions.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A generator class for synchronous and lazy-evaluated ranges, `std::generator`, was added in C++23.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A proper task class, `std::execution::task`, was introduced in C++26.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] It is invoked using `std::execution::sync_wait()`, which returns `std::optional<std::tuple<Ts...>>`.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This is an example of C++20 coroutines with the C++26 `std::execution::task` class.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] C# 2.0 added semi-coroutine (generator) functionality through the iterator pattern and `yield` keyword.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Cloroutine is a third-party library providing support for stackless coroutines in Clojure.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] It's implemented as a macro, statically splitting an arbitrary code block on arbitrary var calls and emitting the coroutine as a stateful function.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] D implements coroutines as its standard library class `core.thread.Fiber` for a fiber.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A generator (`std.concurrency.Generator`) makes it trivial to expose a fiber function as an input range (`std.range.interfaces.InputRange`), making any fiber compatible with existing range algorithms.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Go has a built-in concept of "goroutines", a type of green thread which are lightweight, independent processes managed by the Go runtime.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] A new goroutine can be started using the "go" keyword.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Each goroutine has a variable-size stack which can be expanded as needed.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Goroutines generally communicate using Go's built-in channels.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] However, goroutines are not coroutines (for instance, local data does not persist between successive calls).
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] There are several implementations for coroutines in Java.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Despite the constraints imposed by Java's abstractions, the JVM does not preclude the possibility.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] There are four general methods used, but two break bytecode portability among standards-compliant JVMs.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since ECMAScript 2015, JavaScript has support for generators, which are a special case of coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Kotlin implements coroutines as part of a first-party library.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Lua has supported first-class stackful asymmetric coroutines since version 5.0 (2003), in the standard library *coroutine*.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Modula-2 as defined by Wirth implements coroutines as part of the standard SYSTEM library.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The procedure NEWPROCESS() fills in a context given a code block and space for a stack as parameters, and the procedure TRANSFER() transfers control to a coroutine given the coroutine's context as its parameter.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] The Mono Common Language Runtime has support for continuations, from which coroutines can be built.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] During the development of the .NET Framework 2.0, Microsoft extended the design of the Common Language Runtime (CLR) hosting APIs to handle fiber-based scheduling with an eye towards its use in fiber-mode for SQL server.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Before release, support for the task switching hook `ICLRTask::SwitchOut` was removed due to time constraints.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Consequently, the use of the fiber API to switch tasks is currently not a viable option in the .NET Framework.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] OCaml supports coroutines through its `Thread` module.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] These coroutines provide concurrency without parallelism, and are scheduled preemptively on a single operating system thread.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since OCaml 5.0, green threads are also available; provided by different modules.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Coroutines are natively implemented in all Raku backends.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Python has support for coroutines using the `asyncio.create_task()` function.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Racket provides native continuations, with a trivial implementation of coroutines provided in the official package catalog.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since Scheme provides full support for continuations, implementing coroutines is nearly trivial, requiring only that a queue of continuations be maintained.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since, in most Smalltalk environments, the execution stack is a first-class citizen, coroutines can be implemented without additional library or VM support.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Since version 8.6, Tcl supports coroutines in the core language.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Vala implements native support for coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] They are designed to be used with a GTK Main Loop, but can be used alone if care is taken to ensure that the end callback will never have to be called before doing, at least, one yield.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Machine-dependent assembly languages often provide direct methods for coroutine execution.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] On VAXen (in VAX MACRO) the comparable instruction is "JSB @(SP)+".
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] Even on a Motorola 6809 there is the instruction "JSR [,S++]"; note the "++", as 2 bytes (of address) are popped from the stack.
[src:algebraic-effects/coroutine] This instruction is much used in the (standard) 'monitor' Assist 09.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] In programming languages, a **delimited continuation**, **composable continuation** or **partial continuation**, is a "slice" of a continuation frame that has been reified into a function.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Unlike regular continuations, delimited continuations return a value, and thus may be reused and composed.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations were first introduced by Felleisen in 1988 with an operator called ${\mathcal {F}}$ , first introduced in a tech report in 1987, along with a prompt construct $\#$ .
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The operator was designed to be a generalization of control operators that had been described in the literature such as `call/cc` from Scheme, ISWIM's J operator, John C.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Reynolds' `escape` operator, and others.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Subsequently, many competing delimited control operators were invented by the programming languages research community such as `prompt` and `control`, `shift` and `reset`,`cupto`, `fcontrol`, and others.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Various operators for delimited continuations have been proposed in the research literature.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] One independent proposal is based on continuation-passing style (CPS)—i.e., not on continuation frames—and offers two control operators, `shift` and `reset`, that give rise to static rather than to dynamic delimited continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The `reset` operator sets the limit for the continuation while the `shift` operator captures or reifies the current continuation up to the innermost enclosing `reset`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The `reset` delimits the continuation that `shift` captures (named by `k` in this example).
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] When this snippet is executed, the use of `shift` will bind `k` to the continuation `(+ 1 [])` where `[]` represents the part of the computation that is to be filled with a value.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] This continuation directly corresponds to the code that surrounds the `shift` up to the `reset`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] In general, these operators can encode more interesting behavior by, for example, returning the captured continuation `k` as a value or invoking `k` multiple times.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The `shift` operator passes the captured continuation `k` to the code in its body, which can either invoke it, produce it as a result, or ignore it entirely.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Whatever result that `shift` produces is provided to the innermost `reset`, discarding the continuation in between the `reset` and `shift`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] However, if the continuation is invoked, then it effectively re-installs the continuation after returning to the `reset`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] When the entire computation within `reset` is completed, the result is returned by the delimited continuation.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] whenever `CODE` invokes `(k N)`, `(* 2 N)` is evaluated and returned.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Furthermore, once the entire computation within `shift` is completed, the continuation is discarded, and execution restarts outside `reset`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] invokes `(k 4)` first (which returns 8), and then `(k 8)` (which returns 16).
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] At this point, the `shift` expression has terminated, and the rest of the `reset` expression is discarded.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Everything that happens outside the `reset` expression is hidden, i.e. not influenced by the control transfer.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations were first described independently by Felleisen *et al.* and Johnson.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] They have since been used in a large number of domains, particularly in defining new control operators; see Queinnec for a survey.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Let's take a look at a more complicated example.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The context captured by `shift` is `(begin [*] null)`, where `[*]` is the hole where `k`'s parameter will be injected.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The first call of `k` inside `shift` evaluates to this context with `(void)` = `#<void>` replacing the hole, so the value of `(k (void))` is `(begin #<void> null)` = `null`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The body of `shift`, namely `(cons 1 null)` = `(1)`, becomes the overall value of the `reset` expression as the final result.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] This is pretty familiar, and can be rewritten as `(cons 1 (list 2))`, that is, `(list 1 2)`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The part between `reset` and `shift` includes control functions like `lambda` and `for-each`; this is impossible to rephrase using lambdas.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] Delimited continuations are also useful in linguistics: see Continuations in linguistics for details.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The generalized curry function is given an uncurried function `f` and its arity (say, 3), and it returns the value of `(lambda (v1) (lambda (v2) (lambda (v3) (f v1 v2 v3))))`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] This example is due to Olivier Danvy and was worked out in the mid-1980s.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] These unit tests verify whether currying the variadic function `+` into an n-ary curried function and applying the result to n arguments yields the same result as applying `+` to these n arguments, for n = 0, 1, 2, 3, and 4.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function is accumulator-based and eventually reverses the accumulator before applying the given uncurried function.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] which delta-reduces to the result, `11`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function is continuation-based and involves no list reversal.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The following recursive function, `curry_d`, is the direct-style counterpart of `curry_c` and features the `(shift k k)` idiom, using Andrzej Filinski's implementation of shift and reset in terms of a global mutable cell and of `call/cc`.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The heart of the matter is the observational equivalence between `(reset (...
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] (shift k k) ...))` and `(lambda (x) (reset (... x ...)))` where `x` is fresh and the ellipses represent a pure context, i.e., one without control effects.
[src:algebraic-effects/delimited-continuation] The definition of `curry_d` also illustrates static delimited continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] In computing and computer programming, **exception handling** is the process of responding to the occurrence of *exceptions* – anomalous or exceptional conditions requiring special processing – during the execution of a program.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] In general, an exception breaks the normal flow of execution and executes a pre-registered *exception handler*; the details of how this is done depend on whether it is a hardware or software exception and how the software exception is implemented.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Exceptions are defined by different layers of a computer system, and the typical layers are CPU-defined interrupts, operating system (OS)-defined signals, and programming language-defined exceptions.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Each layer requires different ways of exception handling although they may be interrelated, e.g. a CPU interrupt could be turned into an OS signal.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Some exceptions, especially hardware ones, may be handled so gracefully that execution can resume where it was interrupted.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The definition of an exception is based on the observation that each procedure has a precondition, a set of circumstances for which it will terminate "normally".
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] An exception handling mechanism allows the procedure to *raise an exception* if this precondition is violated, for example if the procedure has been called on an abnormal set of arguments.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The exception handling mechanism then *handles* the exception.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The precondition, and the definition of exception, is subjective.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The set of "normal" circumstances is defined entirely by the programmer, e.g. the programmer may deem division by zero to be undefined, hence an exception, or devise some behavior such as returning zero or a special "ZERO DIVIDE" value (circumventing the need for exceptions).
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Social pressure is a major influence on the scope of exceptions and use of exception-handling mechanisms, i.e.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] "examples of use, typically found in core libraries, and code examples in technical books, magazine articles, and online discussion forums, and in an organization’s code standards".
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Exception handling solves the semipredicate problem, in that the mechanism distinguishes normal return values from erroneous ones.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] In languages without built-in exception handling such as C, routines would need to signal the error in some other way, such as the common return code and errno pattern.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Taking a broad view, errors can be considered to be a proper subset of exceptions, and explicit error mechanisms such as errno can be considered (verbose) forms of exception handling.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The term "exception" is preferred to "error" because it does not imply that anything is wrong - a condition viewed as an error by one procedure or programmer may not be viewed that way by another.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The term "exception" may be misleading because its connotation of "anomaly" indicates that raising an exception is abnormal or unusual, when in fact raising the exception may be a normal and usual situation in the program.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] For example, suppose a lookup function for an associative array throws an exception if the key has no value associated.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Depending on context, this "key absent" exception may occur much more often than a successful lookup.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The first hardware exception handling was found in the UNIVAC I from 1951.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Arithmetic overflow executed two instructions at address 0 which could transfer control or fix up the result.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Software exception handling developed in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Exception handling was subsequently widely adopted by many programming languages from the 1980s onward.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] There is no clear consensus as to the exact meaning of an exception with respect to hardware.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] From the implementation point of view, it is handled identically to an interrupt: the processor halts execution of the current program, looks up the interrupt handler in the interrupt vector table for that exception or interrupt condition, saves state, and switches control.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Exception handling in the IEEE 754 floating-point standard refers in general to exceptional conditions and defines an exception as "an event that occurs when an operation on some particular operands has no outcome suitable for every reasonable application.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] An exception-handling style enabled by the use of status flags involves: first computing an expression using a fast, direct implementation; checking whether it failed by testing status flags; and then, if necessary, calling a slower, more numerically robust, implementation.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The IEEE 754 standard uses the term "trapping" to refer to the calling of a user-supplied exception-handling routine on exceptional conditions, and is an optional feature of the standard.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The standard recommends several usage scenarios for this, including the implementation of non-default pre-substitution of a value followed by resumption, to concisely handle removable singularities.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The default IEEE 754 exception handling behaviour of resumption following pre-substitution of a default value avoids the risks inherent in changing flow of program control on numerical exceptions.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] For example, the 1996 Cluster spacecraft launch ended in a catastrophic explosion due in part to the Ada exception handling policy of aborting computation on arithmetic error.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] William Kahan claims the default IEEE 754 exception handling behavior would have prevented this.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] In computer programming, several programming language mechanisms exist for exception handling.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The term *exception* is typically used to denote a data structure storing information about an exceptional condition.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] One mechanism to transfer control, or *raise* an exception, is known as a *throw*; the exception is said to be *thrown*.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Front-end web development frameworks, such as React and Vue, have introduced error handling mechanisms where errors propagate up the user interface (UI) component hierarchy, in a way that is analogous to how errors propagate up the call stack in executing code.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Here the error boundary mechanism serves as an analogue to the typical try-catch mechanism.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] Thus a component can ensure that errors from its child components are caught and handled, and not propagated up to parent components.
[src:algebraic-effects/exception-handling] The error produced by the child component is caught and handled by the parent component.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In computer science, a **generator** is a routine that can be used to control the iteration behaviour of a loop.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] A generator is very similar to a function that returns an array, in that a generator has parameters, can be called, and generates a sequence of values.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] However, instead of building an array containing all the values and returning them all at once, a generator *yields* the values one at a time, which requires less memory and allows the caller to get started processing the first few values immediately.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In short, a generator *looks like* a function but *behaves like* an iterator.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Generators can be implemented in terms of more expressive control flow constructs, such as coroutines or first-class continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Generators, also known as semicoroutines, are a special case of (and weaker than) coroutines, in that they always yield control back to the caller (when passing a value back), rather than specifying a coroutine to jump to; see comparison of coroutines with generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Generators are usually invoked inside loops.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The first time that a generator invocation is reached in a loop, an iterator object is created that encapsulates the state of the generator routine at its beginning, with arguments bound to the corresponding parameters.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The generator's body is then executed in the context of that iterator until a special *yield* action is encountered; at that time, the value provided with the *yield* action is used as the value of the invocation expression.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The next time the same generator invocation is reached in a subsequent iteration, the execution of the generator's body is resumed after the *yield* action, until yet another *yield* action is encountered.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In addition to the *yield* action, execution of the generator body can also be terminated by a *finish* action, at which time the innermost loop enclosing the generator invocation is terminated.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In more complicated situations, a generator may be used manually outside of a loop to create an iterator, which can then be used in various ways.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Because generators compute their yielded values only on demand, they are useful for representing streams, such as sequences that would be expensive or impossible to compute at once.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] These include e.g. infinite sequences and live data streams.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] When eager evaluation is desirable (primarily when the sequence is finite, as otherwise evaluation will never terminate), one can either convert to a list, or use a parallel construction that creates a list instead of a generator.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] For example, in Python a generator `g` can be evaluated to a list `l` via `l = list(g)`, while in F# the sequence expression `seq { ... }` evaluates lazily (a generator or sequence) but `[ ... ]` evaluates eagerly (a list).
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In the presence of generators, loop constructs of a language – such as for and while – can be reduced into a single loop ... end loop construct; all the usual loop constructs can then be comfortably simulated by using suitable generators in the right way.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] For example, a ranged loop like `for x = 1 to 10` can be implemented as iteration through a generator, as in Python's `for x in range(1, 10)`.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Further, `break` can be implemented as sending *finish* to the generator and then using `continue` in the loop.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Generators first appeared in CLU (1975), were a prominent feature in the string manipulation language Icon (1977) and are now available in Python (2001), C#, Ruby, PHP, ECMAScript (as of ES6/ES2015), and other languages.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In CLU and C#, generators are called *iterators*, and in Ruby, *enumerators*.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The final Common Lisp standard does not natively provide generators, yet various library implementations exist, such as SERIES documented in CLtL2 or pygen.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] A yield statement is used to implement iterators over user-defined data abstractions.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Every expression (including loops) is a generator.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The language has many generators built-in and even implements some of the logic semantics using the generator mechanism (logical disjunction or "OR" is done this way).
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] However, most of the time custom generators are implemented with the "suspend" keyword which functions exactly like the "yield" keyword in CLU.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] C does not have generator functions as a language construct, but, as they are a subset of coroutines, it is simple to implement them using any framework that implements stackful coroutines, such as libdill.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] On POSIX platforms, when the cost of context switching per iteration is not a concern, or full parallelism rather than merely concurrency is desired, a very simple generator function framework can be implemented using pthreads and pipes.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] C++11 allows foreach loops to be applied to any class that provides the `begin` and `end` functions.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] It is then possible to write generator-like classes by defining both the iterable methods (`begin` and `end`) and the iterator methods (`operator!=`, `operator++` and `operator*`) in the same class.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Furthermore, C++20 formally introduced support for coroutines, which can be used to implement generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] C++23 introduced `std::generator` in the standard library, making it much easier to implement generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] An example C# 2.0 generator (the `yield` is available since C# version 2.0): Both of these examples utilize generics, but this is not required. yield keyword also helps in implementing custom stateful iterations over a collection as discussed in this discussion.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Perl does not natively provide generators, but support is provided by the Coro::Generator module which uses the Coro co-routine framework.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Example parallel to Icon uses Raku (formerly/aka Perl 6) Range class as one of several ways to achieve generators with the language.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] However, most of the time custom generators are implemented with "gather" and "take" keywords in a lazy context.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In Tcl 8.6, the generator mechanism is founded on named coroutines.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In Haskell, with its lazy evaluation model, every datum created with a non-strict data constructor is generated on demand.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] where `(:)` is a non-strict list constructor, *cons*, and `$` is just a *"called-with"* operator, used for parenthesization.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] which walks down the list and stops on the first element that doesn't satisfy the predicate.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] If the list has been walked before until that point, it is just a strict data structure, but if any part hadn't been walked through before, it will be generated on demand.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Racket provides several related facilities for generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Some sequences are implemented imperatively (with private state variables) and some are implemented as (possibly infinite) lazy lists.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Also, new struct definitions can have a property that specifies how they can be used as sequences.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] But more directly, Racket comes with a generator library for a more traditional generator specification.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Note that the Racket core implements powerful continuation features, providing general (re-entrant) continuations that are composable, and also delimited continuations.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Using this, the generator library is implemented in Racket.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The community of PHP implemented generators in PHP 5.5.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Details can be found in the original Request for Comments: Generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Any function which contains a yield statement is automatically a generator function.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Ruby supports generators (starting from version 1.9) in the form of the built-in Enumerator class.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Java has had a standard interface for implementing iterators since its early days, and since Java 5, the "foreach" construction makes it easy to loop over objects that provide the `java.lang.Iterable` interface.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Or get a `java.util.Iterator` from the Java 8 super-interface `java.util.stream.BaseStream` of `java.util.stream.Stream` interface.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] F# provides generators via *sequence expressions,* since version 1.9.1.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] These can define a sequence (lazily evaluated, sequential access) via `seq { ... }`, a list (eagerly evaluated, sequential access) via `[ ... ]` or an array (eagerly evaluated, indexed access) via `[| ... |]` that contain code that generates values.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] forms a sequence of squares of numbers from 0 to 14 by filtering out numbers from the range of numbers from 0 to 25.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Generators were added to Python in version 2.2 in 2001.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] In Python, a generator can be thought of as an iterator that contains a frozen stack frame.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Whenever `next()` is called on the iterator, Python resumes the frozen frame, which executes normally until the next `yield` statement is reached.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The generator's frame is then frozen again, and the yielded value is returned to the caller.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] PEP 380 (implemented in Python 3.3) adds the `yield from` expression, allowing a generator to delegate part of its operations to another generator or iterable.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Python has a syntax modeled on that of list comprehensions, called a generator expression that aids in the creation of generators.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] Harmony) introduced generator functions.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The iterators package can be used for this purpose.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The Golden ratio generator below returns to each invocation 'goldenRatio next' a better approximation to the Golden Ratio.
[src:algebraic-effects/generator-computer-programming] The expression below returns the next 10 approximations.
